  "id": "diesel-power-firing-order",
  "level": "1",
  "url": "diesel-power-firing-order.html",
  "type": "Subsection",
  "number": "1.3.4",
  "title": "Firing Order",
  "body": " Firing Order  Firing order refers to the order in which each of the cylinders in a multi-cylinder engine fires (power stroke). For example, a four cylinder engine's firing order could be 1-4-3-2. This means that the number 1 cylinder fires, then the number 4 cylinder fires, then the number 3 cylinder fires, and so on.  Engines are designed so that the power strokes are spaced uniformly, that is, each time the crankshaft rotates a certain number of degrees, one of the cylinders will go through a power stroke. This reduces vibration and allows the power generated by the engine to be applied to the load in a smoother fashion than if they were all to fire at once or in odd multiples.  "
